column168: GATX 94022 NOTED RELEASING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED OVER SPILL CONTAINMENT PAN AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES, FERGUSON-HARBOUR, RESPONDED AND FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE VAPOR EDUCTION VALVE DUE TO OVERLOADING.  THE VALVE AND VALVE PLUG WERE  TIGHTENED STOPPING RELEASE.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE UNLOADING FACILITY WHERE THE LOAD WAS REDUCED RELIEVING THE PRESSURE WHICH HAD BUILT UP DUE TO HEAT EXPANSION.

PASCHALL DRIVER HAD 2 STOPS TO DELIVER TOO.  DRIVER DELIVERED 1ST STOP AND WENT ON TO THE 2ND STOP TO BE DELIVERED THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING WHEN THE DOORS TO HIS TRAILER WHERE OPENED THE FORKLIFT DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND A STRONG PUNGENT ODOR.  THE FORKLIFT DRIVER BACKED OUT AND UNION CARBIDE'S CLEAN UP TEAM WAS CALLED INTO TAKE CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.  THE CLEAN UP TEAM DETERMINED THAT THE REMAINING DRUMS OF CORROSIVE ON THE TRAILER WHERE NOT LEAKING SO THE SPILL HAD TO HAVE COME FROM 1 OF THE DRUMS TAKEN OFF AT THE 1ST STOP.  PROBABLY FROM A LOOSE LID.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON.

column168: DRIVER HAD PICKED UP 4 WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID THAT WAS SENT TO ANTIOCH FROM GREENBRIER AND WERE REJECTED AND BEING RETURNED TO GREENBRIER. THE DRIVER WAS IN A REPLACEMENT TRACTOR AND HAD NO LOAD LOCKS. THE LOADER TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT THE DRUM WOULD BE OK AND OUR DRIVER TOOK THEM. ENROUTE THE DRUMS FELL OVER AND 1 DRUM HAD A LOOSE RING CAUSING APPROX 45 GALS TO SPILL. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY SAFETY KLEEN AT GREENBRIER, TN. DRIVER WAS LET GO FOR FAILING TO FOLLOW LOAD BLOCKING PROCEDURES.

Customer refused shipment of portable tank because of the outer metal cage's condition (rusted frame).  While off loading from flatbed trailer the forklift blades pushed the metal cage bottom up into the valve.  The valve failed and the contents were lost. Before the material was contained approx. 10 gallons was lost in our storm drain.  The drain was dormant and the acid was contained in the one drain.  The drain was pumped dry and then flushed with a soda ash solution to neutralize and then flushed with clean water. All flushings were pumped and disposed of.  Spill mats will be moved to the loading dock for faster future response.  All portable tanks of this style are being reevaluated for cage condition and will be scrapped if not acceptable.

AFTER DRIVER HOOKED UP TO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK AND BEGIN UNLOADING, HE NOTICED PRODUCT IN DIKE AREA AROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE SHUT OFF LOADING LINE AND NOTIFIED CUSTOMER.  CUSTOMER CHECKED STORAGE TANK AND FOUND A STORAGE TANK VALVE LEFT "OPEN".  ALL 200 GALS. WERE RECOVERED.  NATIONAL RESPONSE NOTIFIED 7/7/1999 AT 1211 CDT, REPORT #490367
AFTER UNLOADING PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK TTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK, DRIVER DISCONNECTED HOSE AND WALKED IT TO PUMP TO CLEAN LINE. BACK PRESSURE IN LINE RELEASED PRODUCT OUT OF HOSE.

DRIVER WAS PRESSURING OFF PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK TO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE.  AFTER UNLOADING APPROX 15 TO 20 MINUTES, THE DISCHARGE HOSE SPLIT.  PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME AND CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER WAS FILLING THE BODY TANK ON TRUCK BUT HAD THE SCULLY HOOKED UP TO THE PUMP.  HE HAD ALSO SET THE METER WRONG AND WHEN IT FILLED UP THE COMPARTMENT, THE OVERFILL SENSORS ON THE OTHER TRAILER DID NOT SHUT THE LOADING OPERATION DOWN.  DRIVER KNEW HOW TO HOOK UP SCULLY SYSTEM RIGHT BUT WAS CUTTING CORNERS.  THE APPROX. 50 GAL THAT SPILLED WENT INTO THE LOADING RACKS CONTAINMENT SYSTEM.  THE DRIVER WAS PLACED ON PROBATION FOR 90 DAYS AND GIVEN ADDITIONAL INSTRUCTION ON LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: This shipment was discovered to have spilled on a vehicle.  Proper spill clean up procedures were followed and the package was contained in a salvage drum.  The contents of the package were a pesticide.  Paperwork provided by the shipper indicated that it was an aerosol system employing liquid carbon dioxide as a propellant. The outer package did not have any dangerous goods marking or labeling, nor was it sent with a shipper's  declaration for dangerous goods.  It is therefore believed to be undeclared dangerous goods, namely aerosols nonflammable.  F.A.A. agent Aubrey Campbell was notified.  FedEx will hold shipment pending his investigation.

The box started leaking and had a fuel smell so the spill clean up specialist cleaned up the spill properly and drummed the package. This was found to be an aviation part that contained fuel that was not packaged internally to prevent fuel leakage.  There were no dangerous goods markings or labelings on the outer box and no dangerous goods paperwork was given to FedEx.  The FAA was notified and this package is being held pending the FAA investigation.

The shipment was being processed during the inbound package sort when the discrepancy was discovered.  Apparently the package was leaking during handling.  The package was isolated opened and examined to reveal an aircraft fuel cell.  The unit had not been properly drained of fuel.  The unit leaked resulting in the release of the material.  The spill was contained and the package was placed into a salvage drum.  There were no hazmat markings or labels exhibited on the outer surface of the package nor was there a shipper's declaration for dangerous goods in evidence with the shipment.  The shipment was held pending notification to the FAA for investigation.  The discrepancy was reported by phone to Special Agent Kim Bricker FAA/OKC/CASFU at 10:45 (CST) on 07/08/99.

AN EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING A DRUM WITHIN THE TRANSFER STATION USING DOLLEY. THERE WAS A HOLE IN THE BUNG CLOSURE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUM WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL WHEN THE DRUM WAS TIPPED WHILE BEING MOVED. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE WAREHOUSE. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACKED ALONG WITH THE ABSORBENT PADS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY THREE POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD, SMITHFIELD KY FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WHO SHIPPED THE MATERIAL WAS COUNSELED ON CHECKING THE INTEGRITY OF ALL WASTE CONTAINERS PRIOR TO ACCEPTING ANY MATERIAL FOR SHIPMENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ONE OF OUR ROUTE DRIVERS WAS INVOLVED IN TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WHILE DRIVING A BRANCH TRUCK HAULING WASTE DRUMS. THE VEHICLE ENDED UP ON A DITCH AND RESULTED IN ONE OF THE WASTE DRUMS LOSING A BUNG. THE 30 GALLON DRUM THAT LOST A BUNG LEAKED APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF WASTE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN. THE WASTE WAS ABSORBED AND PACKED ALONG WITH THE LEAKING DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK. THIS INCIDENT GENERATED APPROXIMATELY EIGHT POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 224 EAST MAIN STREET, W. BROOKFIELD, MA THE DRIVER REVIEWED DRUM INSPECTION AND LOAD LOCKING PROCEDURES. DRIVER WAS ALSO COUNSELED ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING TECHNIQUES.

WHILE THE DRIVER UNLOADED DRUMMED WASTE FROM HIS TRUCK INTO THE WAREHOUSE HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM ONE DRUM ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR. THE LEAKING 30 GALLON DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED INTO A 55 GALLON METAL DRUM. THE APPROXIMATELY, 3 OUNCES OF WASTE SPILLED ON THE FLOOR WERE ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO ANOTHER WASTE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF MATERIAL LEAKAGE IN THE WASTE HAULING VEHICLE. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF ADDITIONAL WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER ROAD, DENTON TX FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS BRIEFED TO USE MORE CARE WHILE UNLOADING DRUMS FROM HIS VEHICLE.

column168: A 55 GALLON DRUM OF HCL WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT TRUCK AT LOADING DOCK #52.  THE DRUM WAS MOVED TO A REMOTE LOCATION NEXT TO THE OLD WASH RACK.  AN ESTIMATED 20 GALLONS OF HCL WERE RELEASED FROM THE DRUM. SAIA PERSONAL REMOVED THE DRUM FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND TURNED THE DAMAGED PART OF THE DRUM UP TO STOP ADDITIONAL PRODUCT FROM LEAKING FROM THE DRUM.  REMTECH WAS CALLED AT 1:14 AM AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 2:20AM. SAIA PERSONAL HAD BROADCAST OIL DRY AROUND THE DOCK AREA AND SETUP A LARGE EXHAUST FAN TO DIVERT VAPORS AWAY FROM THE LOADING DOCK AREA.  TRAILER NUMBER 481092 ALSO CONTAINED CANNED FOOD, APPAREL, DRINKING CUPS, BATTERIES, A PUMP AND OTHER FREIGHT AS INDICATED BY THE ENCLOSED SHIPPING PAPERS.  A HCL MIST WAS COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND FROM THE END OF THE LOADING DOCK AT THE TIME OF REMTECH'S ARRIVAL ON SCENE. REMTECH IMPLEMENTED THE FOLLOWING REMEDIAL ACTION TASKS: 1. CLEANED UP DOCK AREA AND IMMEDIATE PARKING AREA NEXT TO LOADING DOCK #52. NEUTRALIZED AREA WITH SODA ASH.  CONTAINERIZED RESIDUE IN TWO 55-GALLON POLY DRUMS.  2. OVERPACKED LEAKING DRUM IN 95-GALLON POLY OVERPACK.  3. CLEANED UP AN NEUTRALIZED SPILL RESIDUES AROUND AND UNDER TRAILER.  4. REMOVED FREIGHT FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  FREIGHT CONSISTED ON 3 PALLETS OF CANNED FOOD; THREE DRUMS OF HCL (PLUS THE 1 DRUM, WHICH WAS OVERPAKCED) AND APPAREL (GYM SHORTS AND SHIRTS, ETC.).  5. CONTAINERIZED DAMAGED FREIGHT AND CARDBOARD SATURATED WITH HCL (MOSTLY APPAREL) IN 8 55-GALLON POLY DRUMS.  6. NEUTRALIZED WOOD FLOOR OF TRAILER WITH SODA ASH SOLUTION. COLLECTED RINSEATES AND PLACED IN DRUMS.  RINSED TRAILER FLOOR WITH WATER. PREPARED FREIGHT DISPOSITION FAX REGARDING RECOMMENDED ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH PROCEDURES FOR HANDLING FREIGHT (SEE- ATTACHED FAX AND SHIPPING DOCUMENTS).  8.  NEUTRALIZED PACKAGING AND OIL DRY SPILL RESIDUES AND SOLIDIFIED.  TRANSPORTED AND DISPOSED OF 10 DRUMS OF SPILL RESIDUE AND CONTAIMINATED ARTICLES AND FOR DISPOSAL AT WASTE MANAGEMENT'S PINE BLUFF SUBTITLE D DISPOSAL FACILITY. 1 OVERPACKED DRUM WITH SPILL RESIDUES WAS DISPOSED OF AT ALTERNATE ENERGY IN AUGUSTA, GEORGIA.  9. PREPARED INCIDENTS REPONSE REPORT.

I WAS CONTACTED AND INSTRUCTED THEM TO SEND THEIR DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL CLEANUP PERSON TO THE VEHICLE TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAKAGE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE IT WAS SUSPECTED THAT THE LEAK OCCURRED DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE ON THE INNER PLASTIC BOTTLE. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING THE INCIDENT. THE EMPLOYEE WAS NOT INJURED, BUT DID REPORT TO THE DOCTOR BUT THERE WERE NO FURTHER PROBLEMS REGARDING HER HEALTH. THE SHIPPER PICKED UP THE LEAKING PACKAGE FROM THE FED EX FACILITY.

column168: AIR FREIGHT SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGED IN PLASTIC CANS WAS BEING TENDERED AT KOREAN AIRLINES CARGO AT OHARE INT'L AIRPORT/CHICAGO IL. DRIVER NOTICED LEAKAGE FROM BOTTOM OF SKID WHILE CARGO STILL ON EMERY TRUCK WHILE PARKED AT THE AIRLINES. AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED SHORTLY THEREAFTER. FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED PUNCTURED CONTAINER INTO METAL DRUM AND ADVISED DRIVER TO RETURN TO OUR FACILITY. SPILL RESPONSE TEAM THEN ARRIVED TO DISPOSE OF MATERIAL AND CLEAN EMERY VEHICLE. NO OUTSIDE CONTAMINATION EVIDENT AND NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. CAUSE OF LEAK DUE TO NAIL PROTRUDING FROM BOTTOM OF SHIPPER PROVIDED SKID WHICH PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS.

WHILE DRIVER ON INTERSTATE 10 EASTBOUND DRIVER HIT ROAD DEBRIS WHICH CAUSED A TIRE TO BLOW OUT ON VEHICLE. DRIVER PULLED VEHICLE TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND DISCOVERED A FIRE HAD STARTED. THE LOCAL SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. THE TRAILER CONTAINED 44092 POUNDS OF PARAFORMADEHYDE. APPARENTLY A LARGE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BURNED ALONG WITH THE TRAILER. MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL OF SULPHUR LOUISIANA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP OF THE REMAINING FREE LIQUID WHICH INVOLVED THE  REMOVAL OF RINSE WATER USED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE AND THE EXCAVATION OF SOIL FROM THE AFFECTED AREA. SIX (6) ROLL OFF DISPOSAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

SPILL MITIGATION PRODUCT RECOVERY AND VEHICLE DECONTAMINATION WAS CONDUCTED BY FERGUSON HARBOUR INC. OF JACKSON MS AND THE CITY OF BRANDON FIRE DEPT APPROX. 90 GALS OF PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND TAKEN TO OUR FACILITY IN JACKSON. EIGHT FIRE FIGHTERS HAD HEAT RELATED INJURIES AND WERE TREATED AT THE SCENE. NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE WAS SUSTAINED. PRODUCT IS TO BE DISPOSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATION.

column168: SPILL CLEANED AND WASTE PROCESSED IMMEDIATELY.  COPY SENT TO SALES AND TRANSPORTATION.

ON JULY 23, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 0430 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, GATX 16770 LOADED WITH DIMETHYL SULFIDE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET SEAL WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS BATON ROUGE, LA RAIL YARD.  THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  THE CONSIGNEE DISPATCHED RESPONSE PERSONNEL TO THE SCENE. RESPONSE CREW FOUND THE CAR TO BE EQUIPPED WITH THE WRONG TYPE OF MANWAY COVER SEAL.  THE MANWAY SEAL WAS REPLACED WITH THE CORRECT TYPE AND THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.  NO EXPOSURE PERSONAL INJURIES WERE REPORTED FROM THIS INCIDENT.

ON JULY 20, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 A RAIL ROAD TANK CAR, UTLX 80732, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A LOOSE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE MOUNTING BOLT, LOCATED ON TOP OF THE CAR, WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS BEAUMONT, TX RAIL YARD.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SITE.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY THE SHIPPER RESPONSE CREW AND THE CAR WAS SWITCHED BACK INTO THE SHIPPERS PLANT FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION.  NO EXPOSURE INJURIES WERE REPORTED FROM THIS RELEASE.

DURING THE TRANSFER OF THE AN SOLUTION FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE STORAGE TANK, THE TRANSFER HOSE CAME LOOSE FROM THE FITTING WHERE IT COUPLED TO THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK WHICH STOPPED THE FLOW OF AN-SOLUTION FROM IT.  THERE WAS NO EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE ON THE STORAGE TANK AND IT TOOK MORE TIME TO GET TO IT AND CLOSE THE VALVE RESULTING IN A LARGER SPILL.  AFTER INSPECTION OF THE HOSE AND FITTING IT APPEARS THAT THE BANDS THAT SECURE THE HOSE TO THE FITTING WERE NOT TIGHTENED SUFFICIENTLY, ALLOWING THE HOSE TO BLOW OFF UNDER PRESSURE.  IN RESPONSE TO HOW WE COULD TAKE ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.  (1) WE ARE REVIEWING OUR TRANSFER HOSE PRESSURE TESTING PROCEDURES, AND WILL MAKE WHATEVER CHANGES NECESSARY TO INSURE THAT THIS WON'T HAPPEN AGAIN. (2) THERE SHOULD BE AN EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE INSTALLED ON THE STORAGE TANK SO THAT IN CASE OF AN EMERGENCY THE FLOW FROM THE TANK COULD BE SHUT OFF IMMEDIATELY.  (3) THERE SHOULD BE A CONTAINMENT AREA BUILT WHERE THE CARGO TANKS UNLOAD, SO THAT IF THERE IS AN EMERGENCY, NO MATERIAL WILL BE RELEASED TO THE GROUND.

FOR REMAINDER OF TRIP, WHENEVER STOPPED, DRIVER OPENED TRAILER DOORS TO ALLOW HEAT ESCAPE. column168: CARRIERS DRIVER CHECKED HER VEHICLE WHILE STOPPED IN REST AREA. WHEN SHE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR SHE FOUND AN UNKNOWN LIQUID ON THE FLOOR. SHE ALSO NOTED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS ATTACKING THE TRAILER DOOR SEAL. SHE THEN DISCOVERED LIQUID LEAKING FROM FRONT OF THE TRAILER. SHE PLACED ABSORBENT PADS FROM HER SPILL KIT UNDER EACH POINT OF LEAKAGE. CARRIER DETERMINED THAT A CONTRACTOR WOULD BE NEEDED AND RETAINED ONE. CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ASSESSED SITUATION AND LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM NEAR THE TALL OF THE TRAILER. THEY REMOVED AND OVERPACKED IT. SINCE THE MATERIAL HAD FLOWED OVER THE ENTIRE LENGTH OF THE TRAILER FLOOR IT WAS STILL NECESSARY TO UNLOAD AND DECONTAMINATE IT. A FIXED FACILITY WAS LOCATED IN THE VICINITY WHERE THE WORK COULD BE PERFORMED MORE SAFELY. THE CONTRACTOR WAS ABLE TO ENSURE THAT NO FURTHER ESCAPE OF MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR WOULD OCCUR. THEY REMOVED THE CARRIERS ABSORBENT PADS FROM THE REST AREA PAVEMENT AND DECONTAMINATED THE SURFACE. WHEN THE CARRIERS OTHER VEHICLE ARRIVED THE ENTIRE OPERATION WAS SHIFTED TO THE FIXED FACILITY. THERE THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER WAS UNLOADED. THE FREIGHT AND FLOOR WERE DECONTAMINATED. MOST OF THE FREIGHT WAS LOADED ONTO THE SECOND TRAILER BUT OVERPACKED LEAKING DRUM AND BALANCE OF THAT SHIPMENT WERE LEFT ON THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE FACILITY AND SECURED HIS OPERATIONS. BOTH VEHICLES PROCEEDED TO THE CARRIERS PASADENA, TEXAS FACILITY. SHORTLY AFTER ARRIVAL AT THE LOCATION ONE ADDITIONAL DRUM DEVELOPED A LEAK. A LOCAL CONTRACTOR WAS RETAINED TO OVERAPCK IT. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS INSPECTED. WHILE NO OTHERS WERE LEAKING ALL WERE DETERMINED TO BE IN UNSATISFACTORY CONDITION FOR FURTHER TRANSIT. AT THAT POINT WITH THE CONCURRENCE OF THE SHIPPER THE DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT TO NEW DRUMS. ONCE DONE THE MATERIAL DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE FAILED NOW EMPTY DRUMS WERE RETURNED THE CARRIERS HOME FACILITY AND ARE BEING RETAINED FOR EXPERT INSPECTION.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MEETING A MIDLAND TRANSPORTATION DRIVER TO MAKE AN EXCHANGE OF TRAILERS. HE WAS CHECKING HIS LOAD WHEN HE NOTICED THE LEAK. HE AND THE MIDLAND DRIVER WERE LOOKING AT THE LOAD WHEN OUR DRIVER WAS HIT BY THE FUMES HE WAS TAKEN TO HEARTLAND REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER IN ST. JOE MO. WHEN HE WAS RELEASED AT 10:30 AM ON THE 27TH HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK STOP AND WAS ABLE TO TAKE HIS TRUCK AND RETURN TO SIOUX FALLS. WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS GONE FROM THE SITE THE MIDLAND DRIVER CALLED MIDLAND AND THEY CALLED THE MOUND FIRE DEPT. THEY ALSO HAD SOMEONE COME OUT AND COLLECT THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEAN UP THE TRAILER. THE LEAKING MATERIALS WERE NEVER BROUGHT TO SIOUX FALLS. THIS INCIDENT WAS DOCUMENTED BY MIKE HALEY WHO WAS OUR SAFETY DIRECTOR AT THE TIME. HE HAD INDICATED AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THAT MIDLAND TRANSPORTATION HAD TAKEN CARE OF ALL THE SPILL AND CLEAN UP. I AM REPORTING BASED ON HIS NOTES AND BY WHAT HE TOLD ME. MIKE HALEY NO LONGER WORKS FOR SIOUX FALLS CARTAGE. THIS IS WHY I DON't HAVE EXACT DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT. THESE ARE THE FACTS AS TO THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE.

THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE CAR WAS POSITIONED ON ITS SIDE RESULTING IN THE LEAKING OF PRODUCT THROUGH THE VENT PIPE.  THE VENT PIPE WAS TIGHTENED AND SUBSEQUENT MINOR LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO AN EMPTY HYDROGEN PEROXIDE TANK CAR AND DELIVERED TO FINAL DESTINATION.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: DURING A ROUTINE SHIPMENT OF APPROXIMATELY 7.3 YD3 OF BY-PRODUCT MATERIAL CONTAINING RESIDUAL NATURAL URANIUM, A SMALL LEAK OF LIQUID OCCURRED FROM THE GASKETED REAR DOOR OF THE STEEL 30-YARD SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ON A RURAL STRETCH OF HIGHWAY 487.  IN ACCORDANCE WITH COMPANY PROCEDURES, THE DRIVER TELEPHONED POWER RESOURCES, INC. (PRI) AS SOON AS THE LEAK HAD BEEN DETECTED.  PRI PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE WITH SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIALS AND RADIATION MONITORING EQUIPMENT.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3-5 GALLONS OF LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE PAVEMENT NEXT TO THE HIGHWAY.  DUE TO THE HOT TEMPERATURE, THE LIQUID QUICKLY EVAPORATED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT VIBRATION PROBABLY CAUSED RESIDUAL WATER TO COME OUT OF THE MATERIAL, WHICH THEN LEAKED THROUGH A HOLE WORN IN THE PLASTIC LINER AND THROUGH THE RUBBER GASKET ON THE REAR DOOR.  THE DRIED MATERIAL ON THE PAVEMENT WAS CLEANED UP AND SURVEYED WITH MONITORING EQUIPMENT.  THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO PERSONNEL INVOLVED AT THE SCENE, THE PUBLIC OR THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE MINOR AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WHICH LEAKED WAS MANY TIMES LESS THAN THE RQ ( REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF 0. 1 CI). IN ORDER THAT THE SHIPMENT COULD PROCEED TO THE DESTINATION, BENTONITE WAS ADDED TO THE REAR OF THE DUMPSTER TO SEAL THE LEAK AT THE REAR DOOR.  THE SHIPMENT CONTINUED ON THE REMAINING 12 MILES OF TRANSPORT WITHOUT ANY ADDITIONAL INCIDENTS.  PRI PERSONNEL FOLLOWED CLOSE BEHIND TO ENSURE THAT THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE, EFFORTS HAVE BEEN INSTITUTED THAT THE LOAD IS AS DRY AS POSSIBLE PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  MORE DURABLE INNER PLASTIC LINERS ARE NOW UTILIZED.

column168: DRIVER GOT OFF ROAD AND WAS PULLED INTO A CULVERT ROLLING THE TRUCK OVER. IT CAUGHT FIRE.  THE FIRE DEPT. WAS CALLED ALONG WITH EPA AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY.  AS FOR FUTURE, PICTURES WERE SHOWN TO ALL EMPLOYEES TO MAKE THEM REALIZE THE POTENTIAL DANGER-DAILY.   WE DISCUSSED THE NEED TO JUDGE WHEN TO TRY TO RETURN TO THE ROAD SAFETY AND WHEN TO ALLOW THE TRUCK TO GO INTO A FIELD OR DITCH.  HOW A MOMENTARY LOOK IN A REAR VIEW MIRROR CAN PULL YOU IN AN UNSAFE DIRECTION.  NOW HAD THE DRIVER BEEN GOING FASTER ON A COUNTY ROAD, HE WOULD PROBABLY BE DEAD.

column168: OBSERVATIONS UPON ARRIVAL:  ON JULY 12, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1157 HOURS, I RESPONDED TO A COMMERCIAL VEHICLE CRASH AT THE JUNCTION OF SOUTHWICK ROAD AND CEDAR RIDGE ROAD.  THE CRASH WAS REPORTED AS ONE VEHICLE, NON-INJURY, AND IT WAS REPORTED TO BE A TANKER TRUCK LEAKING DIESEL AND HOT TAR.  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CRASH SCENE, I REQUESTED THE IDAHO STATE POLICE REGIONAL COMMUNICATIONS CENTER (RCC) NOTIFY CVS AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM.  UPON ARRIVAL, I SAW A WHITE TANKER TRUCK THAT HAD OVERTURNED AND WAS NOW RESTING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE AGAINST THE WEST EMBANKMENT OF CEDAR RIDGE ROAD.  THE TANK TRAILER THAT WAS BEING PULLED BY THE TRUCK HAD COME TO A REST A SHORT DISTANCE BEHIND THE TRUCK.  THE TRAILER HAD NOT OVERTURNED. SEVERAL PASSERSBY HAD STOPPED TO OFFER ASSISTANCE.  A LOG TRUCK WAS PARKED IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF CEDAR RIDGE ROAD BLOCKING TRAFFIC.  THE POTLATCH RIVER WAS APPROXIMATELY TWENTY YARDS TO THE EAST OF THIS LOCATION. ACTION AFTER ARRIVAL, IN ORDER OF SEQUENCE: I ARRIVED ON SCENE AND PARKED BEHIND THE LOG TRUCK IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE.  MY EMERGENCY LIGHTS WERE ALREADY ACTIVATED.  I ATTEMPTED TO GET THE PEOPLE ON SCENE TO COME BACK AND STAND BEHIND MY PATROL , I THEN ATTEMPTED TO DETERMINE IF THE DRIVER WAS ON SCENE.  THE PEOPLE AT THE CRASH SITE TOLD ME HE HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE BECAUSE HE HAD BEEN COVERED IN DIESEL DURING THE SPILL.  I RELAYED WHAT INFORMATION I HAD AT THAT TIME TO THE RCC.  CPL. WALLY YOUNGREN OF THE IDAHO STATE POLICE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND PARKED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE CRASH SCENE BLOCKING TRAFFIC FROM ENTERING.  A FIRE ENGINE FROM THE IDAHO STATE DEPARTMENTS OF LANDS, WITH A THREE MAN CREW, ARRIVED ON SCENE AND OFFERED ASSISTANCE. THE ENGINE OPERATOR ALSO PARKED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE CRASH SCENE.  I DETERMINED THAT THE TANKER TRUCK WAS PLACARDED WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIAL NUMBER 1203.  THIS IDENTIFIED THE SUBSTANCE AS GASAHOL.  CPL. YOUNGREN THEN RELAYED THIS INFORMATION ALONG WITH AN ESTIMATE OF THE SIZE OF THE SPILL TO THE RCC.  I WALKED THROUGH THE CRASH SCENE AND SAW THAT NONE OF THE DIESEL SPILL HAD RUN DIRECTLY INTO THE RIVER.  THE SPILL HAD FLOWED OVER THE ROADWAY AND INTO THE GRAVEL TURNOUT TO THE EAST NEXT TO THE RIVER.  I TALKED WITH THE PEOPLE ON SCENE AND CONCLUDED THAT NO ONE THERE HAD WITNESSED THE CRASH, ONLY STOPPED TO HELP.  SGT LARRY TOMLINSON OF THE IDAHO STATE POLICE ARRIVED ON SCENE NEXT.  I DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH HIM.  I NOTED THE LICENSE PLATE OF THE TANKER TRUCK AS WELL AS THE COMPANY NAME AND USDOT NUMBER THAT WERE LISTED ON THE DOOR. THE COMPANY NAME IDENTIFIED THE TRUCK AS BELONGING TO ATKINSON DISTRIBUTING OF OROFINO, IDAHO.  I RELAYED THIS INFORMATION TO THE RCC.  I TOOK PICTURES OF THE CRASH SCENE.  I STARTED TO COMPLETE THE CRASH PAPERWORK FOR THIS INCIDENT.  SGT. TOMLINSON SPOKE WITH ME AND GAVE ME THE IDENTITY OF THE DRIVER, RODNEY K. GORTSEMA, AND TOLD ME THAT GORTSEMA WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO ST. JOSEPH'S REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER IN LEWISTON.  S

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: A FREIGHT TRAIN 1MBNMX-31 WITH 3 LOCOMOTIVES PULLING 82 LOADED RAIL CARS, 9, 972 TRAILING TONS, WAS TRAVELING WEST ON THE TEXAS MEXICAN RAILWAY MAIN LINE AT APPROXIMATELY 31 MPH WHEN THE LOCOMOTIVE ENGINEER HEARD A LOUD NOISE, STEEL LIKE CLATTERING SOUND UNDERNEATH THE LOCOMOTIVE. THE ENGINEER BEGAN TO SLOW DOWN WHEN THE TRAIN WENT INTO EMERGENCY BRAKING. THE COVERED HOPPER RAIL CAR CONTAINING A HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID RUPTURED AS RAIL CARS COLLIDED INTO EACH OTHER AS A RESULT OF A DERAILMENT OF 12 CARS. THE HAZARDOUS WASTE IS AN EMISSION DUST FROM ELECTRIC FURNACES IN STEEL MILLS. THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS A BROKEN RAIL. THE HAZARDOUS WASTE CAR SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 20 CUBIC YARDS OF THE EMISSION DUST ON TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA ON RAILROAD PROPERTY. THE DUST AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE FACILITY WITH APPROVAL OF THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCES CONSERVATION COMMISSION.

column168: THE INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE APPROXIMATELY 15 MILES WEST OF CEDAR RAPIDS IOWA. DEAN WAYNE VENTEICHER, 48 WAS DRIVING A FUEL TRUCK FOR IRVING F. JENSON CO. OF SIOUX CITY WHEN THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED. VENTEICHER'S VEHICLE WAS SLOWING TO MAKE A LEFT TURN OFF US HIGHWAY 30 WHEN IT WAS STRUCK IN THE REAR BY A SEMI TRACTOR-GRAIN TRAILER. THE IMPACT PUSHED THE FUEL TRUCK INTO THE EASTBOUND LANE WHERE IT SIDE SWIPED A PICK UP TRUCK DRIVEN BY M.R. WESTALL OF ARLINGTON S.D. VENTEICHER WAS PARTIALLY EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE AND WAS PINNED UNDERNEATH IT AS IT ROLLED. HE WAS PRONOUNCED DEAD AT THE SCENE. WESTALL AND A PASSENGER M. WINGER, BOTH ALSO EMPLOYED BY IRVING F. JENSON CO., WERE TAKEN TO MERCY HOSPITAL IN CEDAR RAPIDS WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. THOMAS ANDERSON DRIVER OF THE GRAIN TRUCK WAS NOT INJURED. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 50 TO 250 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE SPILLED ON THE ROAD AS A RESULT OF THE GRAIN TRUCK CRUSHING THE HOSE PIPING AT REAR END OF FUEL TRUCK. THE COUNTY HAZ MAT TEAM RESPONDED FOR SPILL CLEAN UP.

column168: ON 7-01-99 LOVELACE TRUCKING WAS CONTRACTED TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO CARE PETROLEUM, INC. BULK PLANT UNDERGROUND FUEL TANK. CERTAIN EVENTS TOOK PLACE WHERE THE TANK WAS OVERFILLED AND APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF UNLEADED REGULAR GASOLINE ESCAPED OUT OF THE TANK SYSTEM. THE FUEL FLOWED OFF A CONCRETE SLAB AND ENTERED A DRAINAGE PIPE. THE PIPE EXITED FURTHER OFF THE PROPERTY AND FUEL ENTERED A DRAINAGE DITCH. STEPS WERE TAKEN TO CONTAIN THE FUEL IN A 6' X200' DITCHLINE USING A DIRT BERM IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE SPILL. FIRST RESPONSE, INC. ENVIRONMENTAL AND EMERGENCY SERVICES, 1052 SEARCY WAY, BOWLINGREEN, KY., 42103 FURNISHED THE NECESSARY MATERIALS AND EQUIPMENT TO OVER EXCAVATE AN AREA OF DITCH LINE THAT WAS LOCATED BEHIND CARE PETROLEUM'S FACILITY AND ON THE SOUTHWEST SIDE OF RAILROAD TRACK. AN AREA OFF SITE WAS PREPARED FOR THE EXCAVATED SOIL TO BE STOCKPILED. THE GASOLINE-CONTAMINATED SOIL IN THE DITCH LINE WAS EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE SAME OFF SITE STAGING AREA THAT CARE PETROLEUM HAD SETUP. SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN OF THE EXCAVATED AREA AND SUBMITTED TO AN APPROVED LABORATORY FOR ANALYSIS. ON MONDAY, AUGUST 16, 1999 5113 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED WATER WAS PUMPED FROM THE DITCH AND ON FRIDAY, AUGUST 27, 1999 THERE WAS AN ADDITIONAL 725 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED WATER WAS REMOVED. THE CONTAMINATED WATER WAS TRANSPORTED TO CONSOLIDATED RECYCLING LOCATED IN TROY, INDIANA FOR THE DISPOSAL. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS LOADED INTO DUMP TRUCKS AND TRANSPORTED TO DOMERMUTH ENVIRONMENTAL, LOCATED IN MEMPHIS, TN. FOR DISPOSAL. A SOIL SAMPLE WAS TAKEN FROM THE AREA WHERE THE STOCKPILED SOIL WAS PLACED AND SUBMITTED TO AN APPROVED LABORATORY FOR ANALYSIS. ANALYSIS INDICATED THE AREA WAS FREE OF PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS.

column168: ON 070199 AT APPROXIMATELY 915 AM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER, WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR ON TRAIN MBLLI 30 WHICH WAS STOPPED NEAR REEVES, LA INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED THE CAR CONTAINED DIETHANOLAMINE. HOWEVER, THE DESCRIPTION OF THE LEAK WAS NOT CONSISTENT WITH DIETHANOLAMINE. UPON ARRIVAL AT REEVES, REEDER FOUND HIGHWAY 190 CLOSED TO TRAFFIC. REEDER MET WITH LOCAL FIRE OFFICIAL AND MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, NORMAN LEGLUE WHO PROVIDED A CONSIST. WHILE EN ROUTE TO INSPECT THE CAR REPORTED LEAKING, REEDER NOTICED THE CHARACTERISTIC ODOR OF ACRYLATE. CHECKING THE TRAIN CONSIST, REEDER FOUND SEVERAL CARS THAT WERE RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED ETHYL ACRYLATE. REEDER INSPECTED THE CAR FOR REPORTED LEAKING AND FOUND IT SECURE. A CHECK OF THE ETHYL ACRYLATE CARS REVEALED AN ODOR COMING FROM RAIX2712. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, REEDER FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE AND ONE OF THE EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT. THIS INFORMATION WAS GIVEN TO THE FIRE CHIEF WHO THEN APPROVED REEDER MAKING THE REPAIR. UPON OPENING THE MANWAY COVER THE GASKET FELL INSIDE THE CAR, INDICATING THAT IT WAS COMPLETELY OUT OF PLACE BEING HELD ONLY IN THE AREA WHERE IT WAS PINCHED UNDER THE COVER.  A NEW GASKET WAS FORMED FROM GORE TEXT AND THE COVER SECURED. DURING A CONVERSATION WITH THE LOUISISANA STATE POLICE, REEDER DISCOVERED THAT 194 PEOPLE HAD BEEN EVACUATED. A LOCAL TELEVISION STATION KPLC OF LAKE CHARLES ALSO REPORTED TWO MEN WERE TAKEN TO ST PATRICK HOSPITAL FOR EXPOSURE. THE CAR WAS REPAIRED AND THE TRAIN RELEASED AT 1130 AM CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WERE NOTIFIED.

SEABAUGH, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. MR. O'BRIEN FOUND EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE FROM THE LIQUID LINE ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR. ON JULY 2, 1999, THE TUCSON CAR DEPT INSPECTED ABOVE CAR AND FOUND 2 DEFECTS (1. LOOSE BACKING RING ON L-3 WHEEL, 2.  SAFETY VALVE TEST DATE OUT OF DATE.)  THIS CAR WAS PLACED IN BAD ORDER STATUS AND WAS MOVED FROM THE MAIN YARD TO THE REPAIR TRACK LEAD.  FOR UNKNOWN REASONS AT THIS TIME (STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION) THE CAR ROLLED OUT OF THE LEAD AND TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY ONE MILE BEFORE GOING THROUGH A DERAIL AND ROLLING OVER ON ITS SIDE.  DENNIS JOHNSON, MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THE ACCIDENT AND RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE DERAILMENT.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, MR. JOHNSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE CAR TO BE LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE ON THE TOP OF THE CAR AND AT THE LIQUID LINE AT THE END OF THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF THE SHIPPER, THE CAR WAS PARTIALLY UNLOADED WHILE ON IT'S SIDE. CAR WAS BUILT 5-1966.

THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND THE FOLLOWING ATTACHMENT ACCOMPANIED THE SHIPMENT: THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD A PLASTIC SLEEVE AND THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, SIDE 1 AND SIDE 3 HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS ONLY, SIDE 2 OF THE BOX HAD THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME, (METHYL MERGACRYLATEMONOMER INHIBITED), UN1247, A CLASS 3 (FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL). THE FOLLOWING SPECIFICATION MARKINGS, (UN 4G/Y9.S/99 USA/+AX2818 AND THE WORDS (ACCEPTABLE FOR AIR SHIPMENTS), SIDE 4 OF THE BOX HAD AN ADDRESS LABEL FOR THE SHIPPER AND FOR THE CONSIGNEE, HOUSE OF CANS INC., LINCOLNWOOD, IL 60645, PHONE #1-847677-2100 AND THE FOLLOWING FAX #1-847677-2103. THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING: HOUSE OF CANS, STOCK BOXES =, UN1-GAL.PACK, AND THE FOLLOWING MANUFACTURE SEAL: HOUSE OF CANSINC., LINCOLWOOD, IL GROSS WT. 30LBS. column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: While en route from JAN to CNW (about 0730 local CNW time), the crew of Airborne flight 188 (N945AX) noticed an unidentified odor coming from the main deck cargo hold, donned oxygen masks, and radioed the CNW tower for an emergency landing, blocking in at 0752.  After the crew evacuated the aircraft, the local Airborne loadmaster identified the container from which the odor was emanating.  The container was then removed from the aircraft, and containment and decontamination clean up was provided by a hazmat team (fire department) from Ray & Noon E-Systems.  The loadmaster noted that the container had not been properly blocked and secured with available load locks and rails.  The container had then (apparently) shifted back and forth numerous times en route until the liquid in the haz package became over pressurized, whereupon it blew its containment lid off.  Proper adherence to established loading and locking procedures will prevent such incidents.

I notified the FAA and was told to leave a message with Dave King on his voice mail.  I did that and the freight is now being held pending an inspection. The shipment was being processed during the outbound package sort when the discrepancy was discovered.  Apparently the package was dropped in handling.  This resulted in the two plastic containers rupturing and allowing the release of the material.  Further examination of the inner units revealed a marking of methyl methacrylate mononmer, inhibited, flammable liquid.  There were no hazmat markings or labels exhibited on the outer surface of the package nor was there a shipper's declaration for dangerous goods in evidence with the shipment.  The shipment was held pending notification to the FAA for investigation.  The discrepancy was reported by phone to Special Agent Dee Rose, FAA/DFW/CAFSO at 8:30 (CST) on 07/09/99.

EL DORADO CHEMICAL, ARKANSAS CONTRACTED BOOTS AND COOTS SPECIAL SERVICES TO RESPONDED AND CORRECT PROBLEM. MGR. C.T.S. R. SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY MECHANICAL MGR, JACK RUSSELL OF A POSSIBLE AMMONIA LEAK IN THE YARD. MR. SLOANE CONTACTED THE CAR FOREMAN AND WAS ADVISED THERE WERE TEO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANK CARS, UTLX 80572 AND GATX 55153, IN TANK 25 THAT COULD BE THE SOURCE OF THE PROBLEM. MR. CLOANE ADVISED HE WOULD RESPOND AND INSPECT THE TWO CARS. MR. SLOANE RESPONDED, AND AFTER REVIEWING DOCUMENTATION AND GETTING PROTECTION ON THE TRACKS, INSPECTED THE TEO CARS.TANK CAR UTLX 80572 SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LEAKAGE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1650 HOURS, 7-14-99 APRIA EMPLOYEE STEVE PRESSLER, WAS DRIVING EASTBOUND ON I118 AT DE SOTO AVE IN THE #3 LANE. PRESSLER WAS DRIVING AN APRIA VEHICLE, A 1997 ISUZU. A VEHICLE ENTERED THE FREEWAY FROM DE SOTO CUTTING ACROSS 2 LANES OF TRAFFIC INTO THE PATH OF A SEDAN IN FRONT OF HIM. THE DRIVER OF THE SEDAN SLAMMED ON HER BRAKES. PRESSLER ATTEMPTED EVASIVE ACTION BY A HARD APPLICATION OF BRAKES AND ATTEMPTING TO CHANGE LANES TO THE LEFT. IN DOING SO HE LOST CONTROL OF THE TRUCK CROSSED INTO THE CENTER DIVIDER SPINNING 180 DEGREES AND TURNING OVER ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE. THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED AND NO INJURIES. THE CA HIGHWAY PATROL AND LOS ANGELES FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED DUE TO THE TRUCK CONTAINING A PLACECARDABLE AMOUNT OF OXYGEN COMPRESSED AND REFRIGERATED LIQUID THE FREEWAY WAS SHUT DOWN AND THE LAFD HAZMAT TEAM CALLED. ONCE THEY VERIFIED THAT THERE WAS NO HAZMAT RELEASE THEY STOOD BY WHILE THE TRUCK WAS RIGHTED. AFTER EXAMINATION THE TRUCK WAS DRIVEN FROM THE SCENE. DUE TO THE LACK OF HAZMAT RELEASE AN IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATION WAS NOT MADE. ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO ASCERTAIN THE REQUIREMENTS FOR A TELEPHONIC REPORT IN THIS CASE. UPON BEING UNABLE TO OBTAIN CLEAR DIRECTION FROM ENFORCEMENT ON THE MATTER A TELEPHONIC NOTIFICATION WAS COMPLETED CALL #491431.

column168: File AB6599, Shipper: signature finishes, air waybill #SGA 1824978381 BTL. This is a 5800.1 report only. On 7/23/99, a spill was reported at ABX Air, 145 Hunter Drive, Wilmington, OH 45177. The location of the spill was in our hazardous material sort facility. Part-time spill technicians, Elwood Bohl and Christopher Chappa responded. Upon arrival they donned their personal protective equipment and began their investigation. They discovered a fiberboard box showing signs of leakage. The outer box was marked, labeled and had the following attachments: the top of the box had the shipper's declaration for dangerous goods attached to the top. Side 1 of the box had a flammable liquid label. Side 2 of the box had orientation arrows only. Side 3 of the box had orientation arrows and these markings (ltd. qty., UN1263, Paint). Side 4 of the box was marked (UN1263, to: Acorn Windows Systems, 42 Cole Street, Quincy MI 48202). The bottom of the box had the following manufacturer's seal: Chesapeake fiber packaging, Hunt Valley, MD. Upon inspection of the inner package, the following was found: 1 metal receptacle with a friction type closure. There were no positive means to secure the closure which resulted in a loose closure allowing approximately eight ounces of a one quart receptacle to leak. This shipment did not contain any absorbent. This shipment was repacked into a salvage drum with absorbent due to leakage and forwarded onto the destination.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON JULY 24,1999 AWA RAMP PERSONNEL AT SALT LAKE CITY INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (SLC) NOTICED "SMOKE" COMING FROM A PIECE OF LUGGAGE THAT HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE BELT LOADER. THE AGENT REMOVED THE BAG FROM THE BELT LOADER AND RELOCATED IT TO AN "ISOLATED" LOCATION AND NOTIFIED THE AIRPORT DISPATCH OFFICE OF THE SITUATION. A FIRE FIGHTING UNIT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE LOCATION AS WELL AS AIRPORT POLICE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS OF THE BAG IN THE  PRESENCE OF THE PASSENGER A BATTERY WITH WIRES ATTACHED TO THE CONTACTS AND TERMINATING AT A "PHONE JACK" WAS WITNESSED AND VISIBLE MELTING AND CHARRING OF THE WIRE ATTACHED TO THE "NEGATIVE" CONTACT ON THE BATTERY WAS NOTICED. EFFORTS INITIATED TO PREVENT RECURRENCE: THIS INCIDENT IS NOT A FAULT OF AMERICA WEST AIRLINES. 90% OF INCIDENTS INVOLVING DANGEROUS GOODS ARE A RESULT OF HIDDEN HAZARDS BEING SHIPPED BY PASSENGERS. AN ONGOING EFFORTS TO EDUCATE THE FLYING PUBLIC IS BEING CARRIED FORTH BY AMERICA WEST AIRLINES. THIS OUTREACH CAMPAIGN IS IN THE FORM OF POSTERS, PAMPHLETS AND LEAFLETS ACQUIRED FROM THE FAA THAT LIST HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT CAN AND CANNOT BE CARRIED IN LUGGAGE OR CARRIED ON BOARD AN AIRCRAFT.

AB4588 D&F, SHIPPER: HERMANS WAREHOUSE, AIRWAY BILL ILG8198731240ELA, THIS IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT. ON 7/23/99 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "A" BUILDING SORT FACILITY, PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN CHARLES JONES RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL CHARLES DONNED HIS PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  HE DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX WITH THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS, LABEL 8.  THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD A LIBRA AIRWAY BILL AND AN ADDRESS LABEL TAPED TO THE TOP OF THE BOX.  SIDE 1 & 3 OF THE BOX HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS AND FRAGILE, HANDLE WITH CARE, THANK YOU.  SIDE 2 & 4 HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS ONLY.  THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING: HUGHES ENTERPRISES, 86 LBS, TRENTON, NJ 08619.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT TO CONTAIN REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND. 8 PLASTIC RECEPTACLES OF WHICH 8 WERE MARKED AS FOLLOWS: (IRASPRSE YELLOW R-W, BATCH 031431AB, WARNING: FLAMMABLE LIQUID, KEEP AWAY FROM HEAT AND OPEN FLAME.  AVOID CONTACT WITH EYES, SKID AND CLOTHING, AVOID BREATHING MIST OR VAPOR.  KEEP CONTAINER TIGHTLY CLOSED WHEN NOT IN USE.  USE WITH ADEQUATE VENTILATION.  THE BOTTLES WERE PACKED IN STYROFOAM PEANUTS.  THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES HAD SCREW TYPE CLOSURES THAT WERE SECURED WITH TAPE.  HOWEVER THE CLOSURES WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 OUNCE OF IRGASPERS LEAKED FROM 6 OF THE RECEPTACLES AT THIS TIME I HAVE NO INFORMATION ON THE 2 OTHER RECEPTACLES.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS DOCUMENTED OFF THE INNER RECEPTACLES.  AT THIS TIME WE HAVE RECEIVED 1 MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  WE DO NOT BELIEVE THIS TO BE CORRECT.  THE FAA WILL BE TAKING A SAMPLE TO DETERMINE IF THIS IS REGULATED.  THE ONLY PAPERWORK FOUND WITH THE SHIPMENT WAS A BILL OF LADING.  THIS WAS IN CONTACT WITH THE SPILL AND WAS LEFT INSIDE THE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM DUE TO LEAKAGE AND IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: THIS IS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. 7/27/99 @ 1:01 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN A GREEN C CONTAINER INSIDE D BUILDING OF OR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS CARL BOHL, CHARLES JONES & CAROLYN CORDEY DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TAMARA FLORENCE ALSO RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX INSIDE A PLASTIC BAS INSIDE GREEN C CONTAINER WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THEY OPENED THE PLASTIC BAG, OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND FOUND 2 METAL CANS WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP.  THEY REMOVED THE BUBBLE WRAP AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING: 1 - 1 GALLON METAL CAN CONTAINING "DEFT - POLYURETHANE" LABEL ON CAN INDICATE CONTENTS ARE FLAMMABLE, & 1 - 1 PINT METAL CAN CONTAINING "DEFT-CHEMICAL COATING" LABEL ON CAN INDICATES CONTENTS ARE FLAMMABLE.  BOTH CANS HAD FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURE ON THE 1 GALLON METAL CAN CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF THE CONTENTS OF THE CAN.  THE 1 PINT METAL CAN DID NOT LEAK.  THEY RESEALED THE FIBERBOARD BOX & PLASTIC BAG, PLACED THE BAGGED BOX INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO RO ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THE GREEN C CONTAINER WAS CLEANED BEFORE IT WAS PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE.  THE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR WAS ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA. CLEAR OF SCENE: 2:01.  THIS SHIPMENT HAD BEEN REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND WAS BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER UNDER ABX COMAT AIR WAY BILL #DFW20038290216,MGM.

column168: AT APPROX 11:30 AM CDT JULY 30, 1999 A SPILL OCCURRRED FROM ATRANSPORT VEHICLE IN THE SECONDARY CONTAINEMENT AT MID AMERICA DISTILLATIONS INC MADI.  A CLOUD CAUSED BY THE SPILL WAS NOTICED BY MADI PERSONNEL.  AN OPERATOR, ROBERT FULTON, DONNED APPROPRIATE PPE COATED TYVEK, FULL FACE RESPIRATOR, HOOD, GLOVED & BOOTS AND WAS ABLE TO ACTIVATE THE EMERGENCY CLOSURE OF THE INTERNAL VALVES ON THE TANKER WITHOUT ENTERING THE CLOUD. THIS DID NOT STOP THE RELEASE BECAUSE IT WAS FLOWING OUT OF A CONNECTION ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKER WHCIH HAD NO VALVES.  ALL EMPLOYEES WRE THEN EVACUATED FROM THE PROCESS AREA AND RALLIED AT THE MAIN OFFICE FOR A HEAD COUNT.  THE NEAREST NEIGHBOR WHO MIGHT HAVE BEEN OR BECOME EXPOSED TO VAPOR CLOUD WAS VISTED TO CONFIRM THAT THE WERE NOT IN DANGER AND TO EXPLAIN WHAT WAS OCCURRING.  THE PINEY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE GARLAND COUNTY OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AND THAT IT WAS CONTAINED.  NEITHER ORGANIZATION WISHED OR NEEDED TO RESPOND AT THAT TIME.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS ALSO NOTFIED AND ASSIGNED A REPORT NUMBER 493-328 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY APL PERSONNEL, EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. A DRAYMAN WAS PICKING UP THE CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE NOTED A SMALL PRODUCT TRAIL EMITTING FROM THE REAR DOORS. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACEARED CORROSIVE, IT WAS LEFT IN PLACE AND THE AREA ISOLATED. TEC WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND AND IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. THE BILLING SHOWED MULTIPLE COMMODITIES AS HAZARDOUS. DEVELOPED THE LEAK WAS A 275 GALLON TOTE, NEAR THE DOOR. THE VALVE ON THE TOTE HAD VIBRATED LOOSE, AND THE CLOSURE CAP WAS LOOSE AS WELL. THE VALVE WAS SECURED, AND THE CAP TIGHTENED. LESS THAN A GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED, MOST OF WHICH HAD DRIED ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER. THE INTERIOR AREA WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE TO PREVENT FURTHER TRACKING OF THE PRODUCT. TWO ADDITIONAL TOTES WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN GILA BEND, ARIZONA. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE CAR FOREMAN AT GILA BEND AND DEVELOPED THE CAR HAD BEEN NOTED LEAKING ON A TRAIN (TRAIN IDENTITY NOT KNOW AT THE TIME) AND WAS SET OUT ON THE GILA BEND SIDING TRACK. WHEN THE CAR FOREMAN INSPECTED THE CAR, HE OBSERVED SOME ODORS AROUND THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE CAR. THE CAR FOREMAN STATED HE HEARD A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND, BUT DID NOT NOTICE ANY LIQUID NEAR THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR. DUE TO THE EXTREAM TEMPERATURES IN THE AREA, IT APPEARED THE CAR WAS VENTING FROM THE PRODUCT EXPANSION. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED CALIFORNIA AMMONIA AND ADVISED THEM OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR, AND RECOMMENDED A PORTION OF THE LOAD BE REDUCED. CALIFORNIA AMMONIA MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH BULK TRANSPORTATION, BUCKEYE, AIZONA, TO REMOVE A PORTION OF PRODUCT. LATER THAT EVENING, BULK TRANSPORTATION TRANSFERED APPROXIMATELY 7000 GALLONS TO ONE OF THEIR HIGHWAY TRANSPORTS. THERE WERE NO NOTICEABLE ODORS AT THE TIME OF THE TRANSFER, AND THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS AT 180 PSI, WELL BELOW THE SETTING FOR THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE PRODUCT WAS TRUCKED TO BUCKEYE, WHERE IT WAS DELIVERED TO A LOCAL DISTRIBUTOR. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN YERMO, CALIFORNIA. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ALLEN WICKS, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YEMO, AND DEVELOPED THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN INSPECTING AN INBOUND TRAIN (MPCYR-25) ON YARD TRACK #204, WHEN THEY DETECTED AN ODOR AROUND THE ABOVE TANK CAR.  NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKING PRODUCT WERE OBSERVED.  AS THE CAR WAS PLACARD FLAMMABLE, TI WAS MOVED TO THE BUSINESS CAR SPUR, WHERE IT COULD MOUNTED ON THE TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  IT APPEARED THE VACUUM BREAKER AS NOT SEATING PROPERLY AND WAS ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE VALVE.  THE TEMPERATURES IN YERMO WERE EXTREMELY HIGH, WHICH WOULD HEAT THE PRODUCT AND INCREASE THE VAPOR PRESSURE WITHIN THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO SIT OVERNIGHT AS THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS SUBSIDING.  THE NEXT MORNING, MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO YERMO AND MET WITH AGENT DIPLY.  INSPECTION OF THE VACUUM BREAKER NOTED IT WAS AGAIN ALLOWING VAPOR TO BYPASS AS THE PRESSURE WAS BUILDING IN THE CAR.  THE VALVE COULD NOT BE RESET OR REPAIRED IN THE FIELD.  THE VALVE WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR AND THE OPENING SECURED WITH A TWO(2) INCH PIPE PLUG. CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE REMOVED VACUUM BREAKER NOTED THE GASKET ON THE BOTTOM SEAT WAS DETERIORATED AND CRACKED IN SEVERAL LOCATIONS, WHICH IS WHY THE VALVE WOULD NO SEAT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS ALSO ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR SO THEY WOULD PROPERLY VENT THE CAR WHEN UNLOADING.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ITS PERSONNEL REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD, LOCATED THE CONTAINER, AND OBSERVED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE PINT) ON THE GROUND FORWARD OF THE CHASSIS WHEELS.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO LOT #6 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND INSPECTED.  INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS TO BE 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, AND APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.  MOL WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LOAD, AND REQUESTED TO PROVIDE THE SHIPPER CONTACT.  AFTER CONTACTING THE SHIPPER, WITCO, IT WAS LEARNED THIS CONTAINER HAD BEEN WORKED PREVIOUSLY AT THE GLOBAL 2 RAMP ACCOUNT THE CONTENTS LEAKING.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE DRUMS AND LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS INDICATED SEVERAL OF THEM HAD BEEN DROPPED.  IT IS NOT KNOWN IF THIS WAS DONE DURING THE ORIGINAL LOADING OF THE CONTAINER, OR DURING THE REWORK OF THE LOAD IN CHICAGO.  ONE DRUM WAS LOCATED THAT SHOWED SIGNS OF BEING DROPPED, WHICH CAUSED A STRESS CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE CRACK ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK AND ADDITIONAL DAMAGE.  THE INTERIOR WAS CLEANED OF THE PRODUCT RESIDUE, AND THE DRUMS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE SET ASIDE AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.  ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED, IT WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE HARBOR FOR VESSEL LOADING.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR HANDLING.

SCBA WAS NOT USED DUE TO THE LACK OF AN IRRITATING ODOR AND BUILDING VENTILATION. RECOMMEND TAPE BE USED TO PREVENT CAPS FROM TWISTING OFF.  THE REST OF THE PARCEL WAS SENT ON.

column168: ON JULY 14, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1AM, MR. JAMES NORRIS WAS IN AN INCIDENT IN ALABAMA ON THE NORTHBOUND OF I-59 NEAR THE FORT PAYNE EXIT.  ON - PHONE INTERVIEW WITH MR. NORRIS AT 9:45 AM ON JULY 14;  MR. NORRIS STATED HE WAS DRIVING ON THE NORTHBOUND OF I-59 AT THE 214 MILE MARKER WHEN HE REACHED FOR HIS COFFEE AND HEARD A LOUD CRACK OR POP IN THE FRONT OF TRUCK.  THE STEERING WAS THEN FORCED TO THE RIGHT ONTO THE BERM, THE TRUCK THEN WENT OUT OF CONTROL AND DOWN OVER THE EMBANKMENT INTO A WOODED AREA.  MR. NORRIS SAFELY EXITED THE TRUCK AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED TO THE INCIDENT.  MR. NORRIS RECEIVED A SOBRIETY TEST AT THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT AND THEN RECEIVED A URINALYSES TEST AT THE HOSPITAL FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT. MR. NORRIS WAS FOUND TO BE COMPLETELY FREE OF ANY ILLEGAL SUBSTANCES.  THE SPILL WAS THEN CLEANED UP BY NELSON BROTHERS AND JOHNNIE HARIEL CONSTRUCTION.  KESCO, INC. THEN HAD ONE OF OUR OTHER DRIVERS DRIVE DOWN AND RECEIVE THE SPILLED MATERIAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL OF THE MATERIAL.
